From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Sun, 21 Jun 2026 12:24:55 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] xargs: implement -P (parallel) as a bounded pool reaped
 per-pid
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

`-P/--max-procs` was parsed but silently ignored ("[NOT IMPLEMENTED]") — a
request for N-way concurrency ran serially with no indication. Now it runs.

Parallel xargs is just `(cmd)& … & wait`: spawn up to N children at once and
reap each by its OWN pid via `Child::wait`, never `waitpid(-1)`. That is what
makes it safe to run inside the shared engine process — it cannot disturb the
engine's or sibling boxes' children (and serial `command.status()` already
proved the engine has no rival -1 reaper stealing box-spawned children).

`CommandBuilder::execute` is refactored into `build_command` + `map_status` so
the new `spawn` path constructs and interprets children identically; a
`ParallelPool` caps concurrency at N (FIFO reap when full, drain at end).
Serial (`-P1`, the default) keeps the original `execute` path untouched. `-P0`
means unlimited (usize::MAX); echo (no command) stays in-process.

Verified in a box: 4×`sleep 1` is 4.0s at -P1 vs 1.0s at -P4; all three
parallel jobs' "start" print before any "end" (real overlap); -P0 unlimited
concurrent; a failing child yields exit 123; shebang scripts and the logical
cwd work per child; serial output/order unregressed.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
Claude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_01B5MwFcipu6iwqtMPPwFhXd
